Mark Twain once said:
&ldquo;Philosophy is fatal to prejudice, bigotry, and narrow-mindedness, and many of our people need it sorely on these accounts. Broad, wholesome, charitable views of men and things cannot be acquired by vegetating in one little corner of the earth all one&rsquo;s lifetime.&rdquo;
Actually, the first word he said was &lsquo;Travel&quot;. Read it again with &ldquo;Travel&rdquo; and you&rsquo;ll see that the two are interchangeable. They&rsquo;re similar in that respect.
